  "text": "## Upstream Connection Pool Overflow in Envoyproxy/Envoy v1.31.2\n\n### Overflow State Definition\nThe overflow state in the connection pool is defined as an enumeration value in **envoy/common/conn_pool.h** (lines 96-105). The `PoolFailureReason` enum contains four values, with `Overflow` being the first (line 98), representing when \"a resource overflowed and policy prevented a new connection from being created.\"\n\n### Overflow Detection and Emission\n\nThere are two primary locations where upstream connection pool overflow is detected and handled:\n\n#### 1. Connection Pool Map Overflow (source/common/upstream/conn_pool_map_impl.h)\nWhen Envoy attempts to create a new connection pool for a key (lines 33-40), it checks the `connectionPools()` resource limit. If the limit is exhausted and no idle pool can be freed (line 37), the overflow counter is incremented:\n- **Line 38**: `host_->cluster().trafficStats()->upstream_cx_pool_overflow_.inc();`\n- This is the primary source of the \"upstream connection pool overflow\" error during traffic spikes\n- When `freeOnePool()` returns false (unable to reclaim an idle pool), the function returns `absl::nullopt`, signaling a pool allocation failure\n\n#### 2. Stream Overflow in Connection Pool Base (source/common/conn_pool/conn_pool_base.cc)\nTwo additional overflow scenarios are handled in the base connection pool implementation:\n\n**Max Streams Overflow** (lines 175-180):\n- When attaching a stream to a client, if `enforceMaxRequests()` is true and the max requests circuit breaker is exhausted\n- Calls `onPoolFailure()` with `ConnectionPool::PoolFailureReason::Overflow`\n- Increments `upstream_rq_pending_overflow_` counter\n\n**Max Pending Streams Overflow** (lines 282-286):\n- When a new pending stream is being created, if `pendingRequests().canCreate()` returns false\n- Logs \"max pending streams overflow\"\n- Calls `onPoolFailure()` with `ConnectionPool::PoolFailureReason::Overflow`\n\n### Resource Management Architecture\n\nThe resource limits are enforced through **source/common/upstream/resource_manager_impl.h**:\n- Line 101: `ResourceLimit& connectionPools()` returns the connection pool resource limit\n- Line 88-89: `connection_pools_` is instantiated as a `ManagedResourceImpl` with `max_connection_pools` \n- The resource manager tracks open/remaining connection pools and prevents new pool creation when limits are reached\n\n### TCP Connection Pool Interface\n\nThe **envoy/tcp/conn_pool.h** defines the callback interface (lines 90-112):\n- Line 91: `using PoolFailureReason = ::Envoy::ConnectionPool::PoolFailureReason;`\n- Lines 109-111: The `onPoolFailure()` callback receives the `PoolFailureReason` enum value\n\n### Statistics Counter\n\nThe **envoy/upstream/upstream.h** file (line 732) defines the statistics counter macro:\n- `COUNTER(upstream_cx_pool_overflow)` - Tracks total times the connection pool circuit breaker overflowed\n\n### Summary\nDuring traffic spikes, when Envoy cannot allocate new connection pools due to the configured limit being reached and no idle pools are available for reclamation, it emits the \"upstream connection pool overflow\" error by returning `absl::nullopt` from `ConnPoolMap::getPool()` in **source/common/upstream/conn_pool_map_impl.h** and incrementing the `upstream_cx_pool_overflow_` counter. The overflow state is centrally defined by the `PoolFailureReason::Overflow` enum value in **envoy/common/conn_pool.h**."
}

